00:50:26,523 --> 00:50:29,275
He took me up to the mill,

528
00:50:29,443 --> 00:50:32,611
and he tied me up
and started the fire.

529
00:50:33,697 --> 00:50:35,906
Bobby,

530
00:50:36,074 --> 00:50:38,034
he told me he was gonna kill you.

531
00:50:39,036 --> 00:50:40,995
Fat chance.

532
00:50:42,539 --> 00:50:44,540
I won't let him hurt us anymore.

533
00:50:48,962 --> 00:50:51,464
Are you all right?

534
00:50:54,134 --> 00:50:56,343
Doctors seem to think so.

535
00:50:58,555 --> 00:51:04,060
You know, Shelly,
hospitals are dangerous places.

536
00:51:04,227 --> 00:51:07,396
First of all, they're crawling
with sick people.

537
00:51:07,564 --> 00:51:10,816
And second of all,
that food can kill you.

538
00:51:11,860 --> 00:51:15,738
So if you wanna
get out of here pronto,

539
00:51:15,906 --> 00:51:19,033
you're gonna have to let Bobby
be your doctor.

540
00:51:20,285 --> 00:51:25,414
So let's just have a look here,
Miss Shelly.

541
00:51:28,835 --> 00:51:33,798
Oh, you seem to be
coming along splendidly.

542
00:51:35,675 --> 00:51:37,468
Deep breath.

543
00:51:42,015 --> 00:51:45,684
I'd say you're on your way
to a complete recovery.

544
00:51:56,988 --> 00:51:58,823
You better go.

545
00:52:01,576 --> 00:52:03,410
You're my girl.

546
00:52:06,414 --> 00:52:07,456
Bobby.

547
00:52:10,836 --> 00:52:12,419
I love you.

548
00:52:17,259 --> 00:52:21,554
I guess I love you too.

549
00:52:35,819 --> 00:52:39,905
Yeah, I guess I love you too.

550
00:52:50,333 --> 00:52:51,333
Bobby Briggs.

551
00:52:54,254 --> 00:52:57,965
- What's he doing here?
- He doesn't look sick.

552
00:52:58,133 --> 00:53:01,260
Sheriff Truman, to see this kind
of investigative genius at work,

553
00:53:01,428 --> 00:53:03,512
it's just a real treat for me.

554
00:53:08,685 --> 00:53:10,186
Ed.

555
00:53:12,898 --> 00:53:15,482
How are you doing?
I heard you stopped a couple.

556
00:53:15,650 --> 00:53:18,694
I'm okay. How's Nadine?

557
00:53:19,404 --> 00:53:21,155
Well, she's in a coma.

558
00:53:21,323 --> 00:53:24,116
They say there's nothing we could do.
She has to wanna come back.

559
00:53:24,284 --> 00:53:25,868
How are you holding up?

560
00:53:26,036 --> 00:53:28,245
Well, all I can do is sit here,

561
00:53:28,413 --> 00:53:30,998
thinking about the things
I should have said or done.

562
00:53:31,166 --> 00:53:33,709
Ed, don't be too hard on yourself.

563
00:53:35,003 --> 00:53:37,588
I never believed in fate,
Agent Cooper.

564
00:53:37,756 --> 00:53:39,006
I always felt

565
00:53:39,174 --> 00:53:42,885
you make your own way, you take care
of your own, you pick up after yourself.

566
00:53:43,053 --> 00:53:45,387
Farmer's Almanac?

567
00:53:45,555 --> 00:53:48,307
Albert, I would like to speak to Ed.

568
00:53:48,475 --> 00:53:51,435
Albert, I'll buy you a cup of coffee.

569
00:53:54,231 --> 00:53:56,148
Take a seat, Ed.

570
00:53:59,444 --> 00:54:01,153
I saw this coming.

571
00:54:01,321 --> 00:54:03,030
I didn't wanna believe it.

572
00:54:03,240 --> 00:54:06,492
What's worse is I'm sitting thinking
that maybe there's a part of me

573
00:54:06,660 --> 00:54:09,036
that didn't wanna stop her.

574
00:54:09,204 --> 00:54:10,913
And that's a full load.

575
00:54:12,415 --> 00:54:14,416
When did you get married, Ed?

576
00:54:14,584 --> 00:54:16,835
Right out of high school.

577
00:54:17,045 --> 00:54:19,171
Norma and I had been together
about four years.

578
00:54:19,339 --> 00:54:23,425
Everybody figured we'd get hitched.
That'd be that.

579
00:54:23,593 --> 00:54:26,095
I barely knew Nadine to say hello to.

580
00:54:27,138 --> 00:54:29,890
That spring, one bad weekend,

581
00:54:30,600 --> 00:54:32,559
Norma ran off with Hank.

582
00:54:32,727 --> 00:54:35,020
I was so twisted up inside,
I couldn't see straight.

583
00:54:36,773 --> 00:54:38,023
When I opened my eyes,

584
00:54:38,817 --> 00:54:40,901
there was Nadine,
right in front of me.

585
00:54:42,028 --> 00:54:44,363
There was something so sweet,

586
00:54:44,572 --> 00:54:47,032
so helpless about her.

587
00:54:48,576 --> 00:54:49,910
We drove all night.

588
00:54:50,078 --> 00:54:54,498
Ended up in some little town
in Montana, out past Great Falls,

589
00:54:54,666 --> 00:54:56,000
and I asked her to marry me.

590
00:54:57,460 --> 00:55:02,214
Half joking, half drunk, half crazy.

591
00:55:02,382 --> 00:55:04,675
It was light before we found
a justice of the peace.

592
00:55:05,885 --> 00:55:07,011
And Norma...

593
00:55:07,595 --> 00:55:10,097
Well, she hadn't even
slept with Hank.

594
00:55:10,849 --> 00:55:13,183
The look on her face
when she found out...

595
00:55:15,478 --> 00:55:19,940
Nadine and I, we went up to my dad's
old cabin up in Eagle Pass.

596
00:55:20,150 --> 00:55:22,234
Honeymoon.

597
00:55:22,402 --> 00:55:25,154
I was hoping maybe we'd get around
to talking about a divorce,

598
00:55:26,031 --> 00:55:28,240
annulment, something.

599
00:55:28,408 --> 00:55:30,909
But Nadine was so happy.

600
00:55:33,371 --> 00:55:34,955
And you know, by golly,

601
00:55:35,123 --> 00:55:37,583
I shot out Nadine's eye
on that honeymoon.

602
00:55:39,794 --> 00:55:41,086
What do you mean, Ed?

603
00:55:42,547 --> 00:55:44,381
The first day,
we were hunting pheasant.

604
00:55:44,591 --> 00:55:48,260
Nadine's a crack shot
and we already had a couple of birds.

605
00:55:48,720 --> 00:55:50,262
And I felt good shooting.

606
00:55:50,430 --> 00:55:54,600
Listening to the sound echoing,
roll down those hills.

607
00:55:54,768 --> 00:55:56,143
I fired.

608
00:55:56,311 --> 00:56:00,189
A piece of buckshot skipped off a rock
and caught Nadine square in the eye.

609
00:56:01,024 --> 00:56:02,858
Man, that's a tough one.

610
00:56:03,068 --> 00:56:05,277
She laid across my lap
as we drove back to town.

611
00:56:07,113 --> 00:56:08,822
She never cried.

612
00:56:09,240 --> 00:56:11,367
She never blamed me.

613
00:56:11,534 --> 00:56:14,203
She never hated me for it.

614
00:56:16,081 --> 00:56:18,874
Couple of months later,
Norma married Hank.

615
00:56:19,042 --> 00:56:23,045
So I don't believe in fate.
You make your bed, you sleep in it.

616
00:56:24,506 --> 00:56:26,173
Sorry.

617
00:56:27,300 --> 00:56:29,593
Ed, someone here to see you.

618
00:56:52,700 --> 00:56:55,244
A man in a smiling bag.

619
00:57:05,088 --> 00:57:08,882
Take James right back to the station
when you're done here.

620
00:57:10,093 --> 00:57:12,010
Poor Ed.

621
00:57:12,178 --> 00:57:14,138
Poor Nadine.

622
00:57:14,931 --> 00:57:17,474
- Yeah.
- Yeah.

623
00:57:18,226 --> 00:57:19,935
Albert, why don't you
take this opportunity

624
00:57:20,103 --> 00:57:22,521
to check in at The Great Northern?

625
00:57:29,654 --> 00:57:33,532
Nurse, I really mean it,
you better speak to that kitchen.

626
00:57:54,429 --> 00:57:56,638
Harry, when Albert finishes up
at The Great Northern,

627
00:57:56,806 --> 00:57:58,223
we'll meet back at the station.

628
00:57:58,391 --> 00:58:00,851
I'm ready to lay the whole thing out.

629
00:58:01,019 --> 00:58:02,227
Rocks and bottles?

630
00:58:02,395 --> 00:58:05,230
Chalk and blackboard
will be just fine.

631
00:58:05,398 --> 00:58:08,775
- Jelly doughnuts?
- Harry, that goes without saying.

632
00:58:08,943 --> 00:58:11,987
I'll come back later
and I'll bring some soup.

633
00:58:12,155 --> 00:58:15,073
The food in these places will kill you
quicker than most diseases.

634
00:58:15,241 --> 00:58:17,242
Heh. So I hear.

635
00:58:17,410 --> 00:58:19,369
Now, you know
I have a sweet tooth too.

636
00:58:20,038 --> 00:58:22,206
I've got
a chocolate-peanut butter pie.

637
00:58:22,373 --> 00:58:24,833
Norma, I'm serious.

638
00:58:25,001 --> 00:58:27,294
Bring the whole pie.

639
00:58:29,380 --> 00:58:30,506
I'll bring you two.

640
00:58:31,216 --> 00:58:32,508
Okay.

641
00:58:33,968 --> 00:58:36,512
- Feel better, sweetie.
- Bye.

642
00:58:37,013 --> 00:58:39,223
Bye.

643
00:59:40,285 --> 00:59:41,910
Son.

644
00:59:45,581 --> 00:59:47,207
Dad.

645
00:59:48,793 --> 00:59:51,628
Would you

646
00:59:51,796 --> 00:59:53,797
care to join me?

647
00:59:56,926 --> 00:59:58,510
Okay.

648
01:00:12,984 --> 01:00:14,318
How was school today?

649
01:00:16,904 --> 01:00:18,697
School?

650
01:00:20,491 --> 01:00:22,159
Fine.

651
01:00:23,119 --> 01:00:24,786
That's good.

652
01:00:28,166 --> 01:00:29,958
How was work?

653
01:00:31,002 --> 01:00:33,003
Work? Work was good.

654
01:00:41,262 --> 01:00:43,430
- Dad?
- Yes, son?

655
01:00:45,308 --> 01:00:48,769
What is it that you do, exactly?

656
01:00:50,271 --> 01:00:52,356
That's classified.

657
01:00:53,608 --> 01:00:54,775
Oh.

658
01:00:58,571 --> 01:01:01,156
Bobby, would you care
for a piece of pie?

659
01:01:02,200 --> 01:01:04,910
The huckleberries are particularly
delicious today.

660
01:01:05,119 --> 01:01:07,788
Particularly fresh and delicious.

661
01:01:09,374 --> 01:01:11,083
No, thanks.

662
01:01:18,424 --> 01:01:20,133
Bobby,

663
01:01:21,552 --> 01:01:23,261
may I share something with you?

664
01:01:24,680 --> 01:01:26,014
Okay.

665
01:01:26,474 --> 01:01:29,559
A vision I had in my sleep last night.

666
01:01:30,436 --> 01:01:32,104
As distinguished from a dream,

667
01:01:32,313 --> 01:01:34,523
which is mere sorting
and cataloging

668
01:01:34,690 --> 01:01:37,609
of the day's events
by the subconscious.

669
01:01:39,278 --> 01:01:40,987
This was a vision.

670
01:01:41,155 --> 01:01:44,408
Fresh and clear
as a mountain stream.

671
01:01:45,451 --> 01:01:48,453
The mind revealing itself to itself.

672
01:01:50,039 --> 01:01:51,998
In my vision,

673
01:01:52,166 --> 01:01:55,877
I was on the veranda
of a vast estate,

674
01:01:56,045 --> 01:01:59,923
a palazzo
of some fantastic proportion.

675
01:02:00,091 --> 01:02:04,219
There seemed to emanate from it
a light from within this

676
01:02:04,387 --> 01:02:07,848
gleaming, radiant marble.

677
01:02:08,015 --> 01:02:13,228
I'd known this place. I had, in fact,
been born and raised there.

678
01:02:13,396 --> 01:02:15,981
This was my first return.

679
01:02:16,899 --> 01:02:22,863
A reunion with the deepest
wellsprings of my being.

680
01:02:24,949 --> 01:02:27,367
Wandering about, I noticed happily

681
01:02:27,535 --> 01:02:31,079
that the house had been
immaculately maintained.

682
01:02:31,247 --> 01:02:34,583
There had been added a number
of additional rooms,

683
01:02:35,501 --> 01:02:40,630
but in a way that blended so seamlessly
with the original construction

684
01:02:40,798 --> 01:02:44,134
one would never detect
any difference.

685
01:02:44,302 --> 01:02:47,804
Returning to the house's
grand foyer,

686
01:02:48,014 --> 01:02:50,640
there came a knock at the door.

687
01:02:52,894 --> 01:02:54,769
My son was standing there.

688
01:02:56,355 --> 01:03:00,233
He was happy and carefree.

689
01:03:01,110 --> 01:03:05,614
Clearly living a life
of deep harmony and joy.

690
01:03:08,409 --> 01:03:10,243
We embraced.

691
01:03:10,411 --> 01:03:14,080
A warm and loving embrace,
nothing withheld.

692
01:03:15,583 --> 01:03:19,377
We were, in this moment, one.

693
01:03:27,053 --> 01:03:32,849
My vision ended and I awoke
with a tremendous feeling

694
01:03:33,017 --> 01:03:36,937
of optimism and confidence

695
01:03:37,104 --> 01:03:38,772
in you and your future.

696
01:03:40,775 --> 01:03:42,567
That was my vision of you.

697
01:03:44,111 --> 01:03:45,570
Really?

698
01:03:45,988 --> 01:03:51,618
I'm so glad to have had this opportunity
to share it with you.

699
01:04:00,211 --> 01:04:05,507
I wish you nothing
but the very best in all things.

700
01:04:05,925 --> 01:04:07,842
Thank you, Dad.

701
01:04:08,219 --> 01:04:11,263
- See you later. Call.
- Okay.

702
01:04:19,522 --> 01:04:21,439
Major?

703
01:04:21,607 --> 01:04:23,650
How was the pie?

704
01:04:23,818 --> 01:04:25,360
Exceptional, as always.

705
01:04:42,086 --> 01:04:44,170
How is Shelly?

706
01:04:45,298 --> 01:04:47,173
I can't talk right now.

707
01:04:48,884 --> 01:04:51,219
Well, how did she like the flowers?

708
01:05:22,918 --> 01:05:26,379
The night Laura Palmer was killed, it
appears she made two appointments.

709
01:05:26,547 --> 01:05:29,591
In her diary she had written,
"Nervous about meeting J tonight."

710
01:05:29,759 --> 01:05:31,968
I now believe this was a reference
to James Hurley.

711
01:05:32,178 --> 01:05:34,054
She was nervous
because she planned to tell him

712
01:05:34,221 --> 01:05:35,680
she didn't wanna see him anymore.

713
01:05:35,848 --> 01:05:38,391
Before she snuck out of the house,
she received a phone call.

714
01:05:38,601 --> 01:05:41,019
We believe it was Leo Johnson
making the second appointment

715
01:05:41,187 --> 01:05:42,729
for sometime later that night.

716
01:05:43,356 --> 01:05:45,607
Laura met James,
was with him until 12:30,

717
01:05:45,775 --> 01:05:48,234
when, at the intersection
of Sparkwood and 21,

718
01:05:48,402 --> 01:05:50,695
she jumped from the bike
and ran into the woods.

719
01:05:50,863 --> 01:05:53,239
We believe she met up there
with Jacques Renault,

720
01:05:53,407 --> 01:05:55,700
Leo Johnson and Ronette Pulaski.

721
01:05:55,868 --> 01:05:58,870
Together, they drove to the foot
of the trail leading to Jacques' cabin.

722
01:05:59,038 --> 01:06:02,707
They climbed the trail, they were heard
passing by the cabin of the Log Lady.

723
01:06:02,875 --> 01:06:05,710
They reached Jacques Renault's cabin
at approximately 1 a.m.

724
01:06:05,878 --> 01:06:08,380
Drugs and alcohol were consumed.
Laura was tied up

725
01:06:08,547 --> 01:06:11,007
and had sexual relations
with both Leo and Jacques.

726
01:06:11,175 --> 01:06:13,551
Waldo the bird was let out of his cage
and attacked Laura.

727
01:06:13,719 --> 01:06:16,554
Leo and Jacques fought.
Jacques went outside and passed out.

728
01:06:16,722 --> 01:06:19,057
When he came to,
Leo and the girls were gone.

729
01:06:19,225 --> 01:06:22,477
We believe Leo hiked back down
the trail to his Corvette alone,

730
01:06:22,645 --> 01:06:24,104
leaving the girls behind.

731
01:06:24,271 --> 01:06:26,523
The reason being,
there was a third man.

732
01:06:26,691 --> 01:06:28,608
Deputy Hawk found
evidence of a third man

733
01:06:28,776 --> 01:06:30,819
outside the window
of Jacques' cabin.

734
01:06:30,986 --> 01:06:33,196
The third man took Laura
and Ronette to the train

735
01:06:33,364 --> 01:06:34,364
where they were tied up.

736
01:06:34,532 --> 01:06:36,449
Laura for the second time,
Ronette for the first.

737
01:06:36,617 --> 01:06:38,660
Using a blunt object,
the killer hit Ronette

738
01:06:38,828 --> 01:06:40,203
and knocked her unconscious.

739
01:06:40,371 --> 01:06:42,330
He must have been so intent
on killing Laura,

740
01:06:42,498 --> 01:06:45,917
he didn't realize that Ronette
regained consciousness and escaped.

741
01:06:46,085 --> 01:06:48,545
Either he didn't know or he didn't care.

742
01:06:48,713 --> 01:06:50,714
He made a small mound of dirt

743
01:06:50,881 --> 01:06:53,258
and put the half-heart necklace
of Laura's on top.

744
01:06:53,426 --> 01:06:57,887
He then placed a small cut out letter R
under the nail of her left ring finger.

745
01:06:58,055 --> 01:07:02,350
You'll recall that he placed the letter T
under the fingernail of Teresa Banks.

746
01:07:02,518 --> 01:07:06,479
He left a note written in blood,
"Fire walk with me."

747
01:07:06,647 --> 01:07:08,148
Here's the interesting thing.

748
01:07:08,315 --> 01:07:11,067
The blood on the note was tested.
It doesn't match Leo's,

749
01:07:11,235 --> 01:07:13,445
Jacques', Laura's or Ronette's.

750
01:07:13,612 --> 01:07:16,698
So we surmise the killer
wrote the note in his own blood.

751
01:07:16,866 --> 01:07:19,492
It's a rare type, AB negative.

752
01:07:19,660 --> 01:07:23,288
The towel that Deputy Hawk found
five miles down the tracks

753
01:07:23,456 --> 01:07:25,039
was soaked in blood of that type.

754
01:07:25,207 --> 01:07:29,043
He also found, near the towel,
scraps of faded paper.

755
01:07:29,211 --> 01:07:31,379
These scraps may have
been left by the killer.

756
01:07:31,547 --> 01:07:34,090
They'll be sent back
to Washington, D.C., for testing.

757
01:07:45,644 --> 01:07:48,688
I know, Andy.
I know, I know, I know.

758
01:07:48,856 --> 01:07:51,733
It's what we call
a real three-hankie crime.

759
01:07:58,032 --> 01:08:00,617
Albert Rozerfeld,

760
01:08:00,785 --> 01:08:05,163
I don't like the way you talk smart
about Sheriff Truman or anybody.

761
01:08:05,331 --> 01:08:07,123
You just shut your mouth!

762
01:08:26,060 --> 01:08:27,894
Laura Palmer is dead.

763
01:08:28,062 --> 01:08:30,271
Jacques Renault is dead.

764
01:08:30,439 --> 01:08:34,067
Ronette Pulaski and Leo Johnson
are in comas.

765
01:08:34,235 --> 01:08:36,444
Waldo the bird is dead.

766
01:08:37,571 --> 01:08:40,740
This leaves only the third man.

767
01:08:56,966 --> 01:09:01,344
- You want this door closed?
- Yeah, yeah. We'll frost our rooms.

768
01:09:02,763 --> 01:09:03,763
Oh.

769
01:09:03,931 --> 01:09:07,684
- I sure do appreciate the ride, Harry.
- No problem.

770
01:09:08,477 --> 01:09:10,478
I always appreciate
your company, Pete.

771
01:09:10,646 --> 01:09:12,480
Oh.

772
01:09:12,648 --> 01:09:19,153
Boy, this smoke inhalation
is nasty business.

773
01:09:20,114 --> 01:09:26,786
I feel like somebody taped my lips
to the tailpipe of a bus.

774
01:09:33,711 --> 01:09:36,254
Take her easy.

775
01:09:38,507 --> 01:09:44,053
- So where the hell is Josie?
- Oh, well, maybe this will tell us.

776
01:09:50,436 --> 01:09:51,603
"Dear Pete,

777
01:09:52,104 --> 01:09:55,315
I had to leave the town

778
01:09:55,482 --> 01:10:01,321
on an emergency
of business to Seattle.

779
01:10:02,072 --> 01:10:05,658
I will phone you when I arrive.

780
01:10:05,826 --> 01:10:09,495
